r parents—in their efforts to make a living together in the United States. Kids at Work provides a compassionate, up-close portrait of Latinx children, detailing the complexities and nuances of family relations when children help generate income for the household as they peddle the streets of LA alongside their immigrant parents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aChild laborzCaliforniazLos AngelesvCase studies. 0aChildren of illegal alienszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aChildren of noncitizenszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aHispanic American familieszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 0aIllegal immigrationzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aImmigrant familieszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aLatin AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 0aStreet-food vendors (Persons)zCaliforniazLos AngelesvCase studies. 0aStreet-food vendorszCaliforniazLos AngelesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh  aAmerican generational resources.  aLatinx sociology.  achild remittances.  achildhood and migration.  achildren and work.  acollectivist immigrant bargain.  acommunal family obligation code.  aconcerted cultivation.  acriminalization of youth.  acultural economic innovation.  adissonant acculturation.  aeconomic empathy.  aethnic economy.  aethnic entrepreneurship.  afamily bartering.  afamily work relations.  agender and migration.  agendered labor.  agendered spaces.  aimmigrant bargain.  ainformal economy.  aintergenerational family dynamics.  ainternational migration.  aintersectionality theory.  aintersectionality.  alegalization of street vending.  amale privilege.  asegmented assimilation theory.  asocial capital theory.  asocialization of childhood.  astreet resources.  astreet vending.